               <msContents>
                  <summary>Prosimetric allegorical narrative of the adventures of prince Buland Akhtar, composed in 1051 (1641-2), by the poet Fānī Kashmīrī (d.1081/1671-2).</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_648-item1">
                     <author ref="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n85073276" key="person_47114320">
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Fānī, Muḥsin, -1671 or 1672</persName> فانى كشميرى، محسن بن محسن</author>
                     <title xml:lang="perLatn-x-lc" key="work_7213">ʿĀshiq u Maʿshūq musammā bi-Hamīshah bahār</title>
                     <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="alt" key="work_7213">ʿĀshiq u Maʿshūq, otherwise known as Hamīshah bahār</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_7213">عاشق و معشوق مسمی به همیشه بهار</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa">عشق گذاشت</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa">زآنکه هم نام هم نشان فانیست تمت بالخیر نسخه عاشق و معشوق مسمی به همیشه بهار بوقت نیک صورت اتمام پذیرفت</explicit>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>This work was previously thought to be a copy of Ikhlāṣ Chand's taz̲kira <title>Hamīsha Bahār</title>. While it is subtitled Hamīsha Bahār, the work's main title is ʿĀshiq u Maʿshūq. The text is not a taz̲kira, but a prosimetric allegorical narrative following the adventures of a prince named Buland Akhtar, as he travels through Kashmir in search of the meaning of love, and encounters kings, dervishes, fairies and ogres along the way. The final line of the work gives the name of the author as Fānī (<locus>f.133a</locus>). The date of the work's completion is given in a chronogram which yields the year 1051/1641-2 (<locus>f.132a</locus>). On the basis of the name, the dating and the contents, the work can be ascribed to the poet Fānī Kashmīrī (d.1081/1671-2). The text appears to be acephalous [JW, 2017].</note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
